The user wants me to implement an LRU (Least Recently Used) cache in TypeScript with O(1) get/put operations. They want the file to be named `lru.ts` and want me to export everything the spec says to export.

Let me think about what an LRU cache needs:

1. A data structure that allows O(1) access - a hash map/object
2. A way to track the order of access - a doubly linked list
3. The ability to efficiently remove the least recently used item - doubly linked list tail
4. Methods: get, put (set), possibly clear, size, etc.

Standard LRU cache implementation:
- Use a Map or object for O(1) key access
- Use a doubly-linked list to maintain order (most recent at head, least recent at tail)
- When accessing (get), move the node to the head
- When putting a new item or updating, move to head
- When capacity is exceeded, remove from tail

