For additional methods like clear() or size, the spec doesn't require them, so I'll stick with just get and put. I'm using sentinel nodes to simplify edge cases when managing the linked list. The Node class stores key-value pairs with prev/next pointers, and the LRUCache maintains a Map for O(1) lookups plus head and tail sentinels to avoid null checks. The constructor validates that capacity is positive.

For get(), I check if the key exists, move that node to the head (marking it as recently used), and return its value. For put(), if the key already exists I update its value and move it to the head; otherwise I create a new node, add it to the head, and if the cache exceeds capacity I evict the least recently used node from just before the tail. The helper methods handle moving nodes to the head, adding new nodes right after the head sentinel, and removing nodes from their current position in the list.

Using sentinel nodes for head and tail eliminates edge cases when the list is empty. I should make sure the LRUCache class itself is exported since that's what the spec requires.

